<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-263-016  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 263 016.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Newsbytes  March 6 1990* Full Text COPYRIGHT Newsbytes Inc. 1990.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>New York subway to sprout fiber cables.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Blankenhorn, Dana.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Company:   Cable Applications Inc. (contracts).andO;Topic:     TelecommunicationsGovernment ContractsFiber opticsNetworksNew York.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>NEW YORK SUBWAY TO SPROUT FIBER CABLES NEW YORK, NEW YORK, U.S.A., 1990 MAR 5(NB) -- Cable Applications, a bypass company, will negotiate a license withthe New York Metropolitan Transportation Authority to install fiber opticcables along the right-of-way along the New York City subway right-of-ways,as well as those of the Long Island Railroad, Metro North Commuter Railroad,and Triborough Bridge and Tunnel Authority.andM;The Metropolitan Area Network will at first consist of a single 14-mile linkthrough the subway tunnels in Manhattan and Brooklyn, connecting 59th Streetand the Wall Street area to the Metrotech complex in Brooklyn.andP;  The term ofthe license agreement will be up to 60 years.andP;  After installation of thesystem, Cable Applications will offer bypass services throughout lowerManhattan.andP;  &quot;I've given myself 60 days to negotiate the license,&quot; saysRichard Capaldo of Cable Applications.andP;  &quot;We're expecting completion in 18months after the finalized license.&quot;andM;Cable Applications has previously installed fiber networks, along with cableand microwave, at such locations as Columbia University, the Sloan KetteringInstitute, and the Consolidated Edison electric company.andM;(Dana Blankenhorn/19900302/Press Contact: Richard Capaldo, CableApplications, 516/877-1700)</TEXT></DOC>